{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638197"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:50:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:50:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17695"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17695"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10409"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72080"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10409"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17695"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57550"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10440"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24320"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24350"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72080"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESound waves travel through the external and middle ear before reaching the cochlea, where they are converted into neural signals. Different regions of the cochlea respond to different frequencies of sound waves.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the relationship between sound wave frequency and perceived pitch?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Higher frequency produces higher pitch","Pitch is independent of frequency","Frequency and pitch are inversely related","Frequency only affects pitch at high intensities","Higher frequency produces lower pitch"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere is a direct relationship between sound wave frequency and perceived pitch - \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigher frequency produces higher pitch\u003C/strong\u003E. This relationship is fundamental to how we perceive sound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPitch is independent of frequency\u003C/strong\u003E - Pitch perception is directly dependent on the frequency of sound waves and cannot occur independently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrequency and pitch are inversely related\u003C/strong\u003E - The relationship between frequency and pitch is directly proportional, not inverse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrequency only affects pitch at high intensities\u003C/strong\u003E - The relationship between frequency and pitch exists at all sound intensities, not just high ones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigher frequency produces lower pitch\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the opposite of the correct relationship, as higher frequencies always produce higher pitches.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis relationship is reflected in the tonotopic organisation of the cochlea, where high-frequency sounds activate the basal region and low-frequency sounds activate the apex. This arrangement allows for the discrimination of different pitches in complex sounds.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The frequency of sound waves is directly proportional to the perceived pitch of the sound.","Higher frequency sound waves activate the basal region of the cochlea, while lower frequencies activate the apex.","The human ear can typically detect frequencies between 20 Hz and 20,000 Hz."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57550"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17695"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57550"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T22:17:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T22:19:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10409"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72080"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"